      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a chemical reaction between amino acids and reducing sugars that gives browned food its distinctive flavor. It typically occurs at temperatures above 140°C (284°F), and it is responsible for the golden-brown color of toasted bread, not caramelization, which is a separate process that involves the heating of sugars alone. The Maillard reaction forms complex molecules that are responsible for flavor and color, while caramelization is more about the simple sugar breakdown and formation of new flavors without the involvement of amino acids.",
